My Role Today
As the Project Coordinator for Group 1, my main focus today was making sure that we didn't just have a "good idea," but a plan that we could actually finish on time. I spent the morning helping the team narrow down our ideas and the afternoon setting up a structure for how we will work over the next few days.

Topic Research & Selection
We started the day by debating three main topics: password safety, online privacy, and phishing. I personally pushed for Phishing Awareness after researching how common it is at Coventry University.

I found that students are often in a rush, checking emails between classes or late at night. This makes them vulnerable to "urgent" fake emails about assignment re-uploads or student finance issues. We decided as a group that our game should focus on this "high-stress" decision-making process. I wanted to make sure the game felt real, so I suggested we use scenarios that students actually face every day.

Developing the "Everyday Dilemma" Concept
Once we picked the topic, I worked closely with Prajwal (our Design Lead) to turn the "Phishing" idea into a game. We came up with the "Car/Highway" metaphor.

I contributed the idea that the "Car" represents the student's personal data.

If the player hits a phishing link, the "blast" isn't just a game-over screen; it represents a real-life data breach where your identity is stolen.

I helped the group visualize the storyboard, making sure we had a clear beginning (getting a suspicious email) and a clear ending (either graduating safely or failing due to a hacked account).

Management & Group Organization
To keep us organized, I helped Shalu (our Chair) manage the time. We made sure the storyboard was done by lunch so we could spend the afternoon finishing our Day 1 worksheet. I also identified a potential risk: if we don't communicate well on GitHub, we might lose our work. My plan to manage this is to do a quick "stand-up" meeting every morning to check everyone's progress.

What I Learned
Today taught me that being a coordinator is about more than just checking boxes; it’s about making sure the group's creative ideas stay focused on the learning goal. I’m happy with our "Everyday Dilemma" concept and feel ready to start building the project structure on GitHub tomorrow.
